text: Recognizing the necessity of network benefits, the concurrence makes this

label: BODY

text: Grid by creating the potential to interconnect significant new and diverse

text: it been made by the CAISO...."
label: BODY

text: This passage has two problems.  First, it does not distinguish this facility from any non-
label: BODY

text: integrated gen-tie.  Any gen-tie interconnects new generation; but an interconnection role
label: BODY

text: alone does not create network benefits.  For network benefits to exist, the transmission
label: BODY

text: ratepayer must benefit in his role as a transmission customer, not in his role as a power
label: BODY

text: customer.
label: BODY

text: Second, the next sentence does not follow from the first.  The second sentence
label: BODY

text: implies that the interconnection of new generation somehow interacts with independent
label: BODY

text: entity status to support roll-in.  But as discussed above, the ability to roll-in depends on
label: BODY

text: network benefits; roll-in has nothing to do with independent status.  FERC created the
label: BODY

text: independent entity variation option because independent entities have no incentive to
label: BODY

text: discriminate.  See Order 2003 at para. 822 ("RTO or ISO should be treated differently
label: BODY

text: because an independent RTO or ISO does not raise the same level of concern regarding
label: BODY

text: undue discrimination.").  The discrimination of concern to FERC was discrimination by a
label: BODY

text: generation-owning transmission provider against independent generators.  Here, SCE is
label: BODY

text: seeking to have its own ratepayers bear costs that generators might otherwise provide.
label: BODY

text: SCE's proposal does not involve discrimination against generators.  The independent
label: BODY

text: entity standard has nothing to do with this matter (as evidenced by the absence of any
label: BODY

text: mention of the issue in the majority's decision).
label: BODY

text: Conclusion:  Since the independent-nonindependent distinction had no effect on
label: BODY

text: the majority's decision (nor should it have, because roll-in depends on network benefits,
label: BODY

text: not on who controls the line), it is necessary for the CA ISO, if it does make the refiling,
label: BODY

text: to adjust the Segment 3 plan so that network benefits are clear.  Moreover, the
label: BODY

text: "independent entity variation" is not available to shift non-network costs from generators
label: BODY

text: to transmission customers.  The requirement that transmission customers bear costs only
label: BODY

text: to the extent those costs benefit the network is rooted in the FPA's "just and reasonable"
label: BODY

text: requirement.  The flexibility granted by Order 2003 to independent entities cannot violate
label: BODY

text: that standard.
